\description{
Controls how data rows are grouped, paginated, indented, and spaced.
Calling \code{fr_rows()} again \strong{merges} with the previous row configuration:
only the arguments you explicitly supply are changed.

arframe uses a two-level greedy pagination algorithm (identical for RTF and
PDF output):
\itemize{
\item \strong{\code{page_by}} forces a page break whenever the named column(s) change
value.
\item \strong{\code{group_by}} keeps rows with the same value in the named column(s)
on the same page via \verb{\\trkeep} (RTF). If a group is too large for a
single page, it breaks normally and a "(continued)" header row repeats
at the top of the next page.
}
}
\section{Regulatory conventions — AE tables}{

Standard pharma AE tables (MedDRA SOC/PT hierarchy) follow these row
conventions:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Sort order}: SOC rows sorted by \strong{descending incidence} across all
arms; within each SOC, PT rows sorted by descending incidence
(alphabetical as tiebreaker). This is the standard regulatory sort order.
\item \strong{"TOTAL SUBJECTS WITH AN EVENT"} is always the first summary row,
above the first SOC. Pre-compute this in your data frame.
\item \strong{Subject counting}: a subject is counted once per SOC and once per
PT, even with multiple events. Document this in \code{fr_footnotes()}.
\item \strong{Page breaks by SOC}: each System Organ Class starts a new page
(\code{page_by = "soc"}). PT rows stay with their SOC header via \code{group_by}.
\item \strong{Indentation}: PT rows are indented under the SOC header
(\code{indent_by = "pt_label"}). Indent: 0.1667 in (2 spaces / 240 twips).
}
}

\section{Regulatory conventions — descriptive statistics tables}{

For demographics and continuous endpoint tables, the standard summary
statistic row order is:
\verb{n, Mean, SD (or SE), Median, Q1/Q3, Min/Max}
Pre-sort your long-form data to match this order. Use \code{blank_after} to
insert visual separation between characteristic blocks (e.g. between Age
and Sex sections).
}

\section{Orphan and widow control}{

The pagination engine respects the \code{orphan_min} and \code{widow_min} settings
in \code{\link[=fr_page]{fr_page()}}. Orphan control prevents a lone row being stranded at the
bottom of a page; widow control prevents a lone row starting a new page.
These apply within \code{group_by} groups: if placing a group would leave
fewer than \code{orphan_min} rows before the page break, the group is moved to
the next page instead.
}

\section{Tips}{

\itemize{
\item \code{page_by} columns are \strong{automatically hidden} at render time — their
values appear as group labels in the section header, so they don't need
to appear in the table body. Override with
\code{fr_cols(col = fr_col(visible = TRUE))} if needed (set \emph{after}
\code{fr_rows()}).
\item \code{group_by}, \code{indent_by}, etc. columns are structural — hide them via
\code{fr_cols(col = fr_col(visible = FALSE))} if they shouldn't appear.
\item Use \code{group_by} (not \code{page_by}) when you want rows to travel together
but not necessarily start on a new page.
\item \code{blank_after} is the simplest way to add visual group separation without
bold headers.
}
}

